  "prompt": "I just bought an Activa 110 cc bike and technicians have advised me against riding it above 40 kmph until the first 750 km. Why is that so?",
  "response": "The recommendation to avoid riding your Activa 110 cc bike above 40 km/h during the initial 750 km, also known as the break-in period, is a common practice for new motorcycles and scooters. Here are the reasons for this advice:\n\n1. **Engine Break-in**: New engines have tight tolerances and need to run at varying speeds and loads to properly seat the piston rings and establish an even wear pattern. Keeping the speed below a certain limit helps to ensure that the engine components wear correctly and optimally.\n\n2. **Prevent Overheating**: During the break-in period, the engine is still adapting to use, and running it at high speeds can generate extra heat. Limiting speed helps to avoid overheating and allows the cooling system to manage temperatures effectively.\n\n3. **Fuel System Calibration**: New bikes will be adjusting their fuel mixture and other parameters as they break in. Riding at lower speeds allows the bike's fuel and engine management system to adjust properly.\n\n4. **Component Wear**: The break-in period helps in ensuring that various moving parts (like the gearbox and clutch) wear in gradually. High speeds can lead to uneven wear and could potentially lead to premature failure of components.\n\n5. **Safety and Handling**: As you become accustomed to your new bike's handling and braking characteristics, keeping the speed low allows you to better understand its response to your inputs.\n\n6. **Warranty Considerations**: Some manufacturers state that not following break-in procedures can potentially void warranties, so adhering to these recommendations ensures you maintain warranty coverage.\n\nFollowing these recommendations will help ensure that your Activa 110 cc runs smoothly and lasts a long time. After the break-in period, you can gradually increase speed as the engine has settled and matured.",
